benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/priceList - Retrieve priceList for a given subscription and date

covered: GET Method - Valid Request: TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04 validate successful 200 responses and correct PriceList payloads for various parameter combinations.
GET Method - Empty Response: TC13 covers behavior when the database lacks data (404 or empty/default response).
Query Parameters: Extensive coverage of valid/invalid parameter combinations (subscriptionId, requestedDate, both, none, and edge cases like extra parameters) across TC01–TC12, TC19, TC22, TC23.
Authorization: TC08 validates unauthorized access returning HTTP 401.
Error handling and resilience: TC09 (service unavailable), TC20 (dependent service unavailable), and TC17 (retry after transient failure) test resilience and error responses.
Security: TC10 (SQL injection) and TC22 (XSS) validate input sanitization and safe error responses.
Performance and boundary: TC14/TC15 test latency under normal/peak load; TC18 covers large data volume; TC21 covers date boundary regression.
Backward compatibility and accessibility: TC16 demonstrates backward compatibility; TC23 addresses accessibility considerations for UI contexts.
gaps: Pagination: No tests verifying API pagination for large result sets.
Caching Behavior: No tests checking caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or cache validation.
Rate Limiting: No tests for throttling or 429 responses under high request load.
Authorization: No tests for 403 Forbidden or token refresh/expiry handling.
recommendations: Add pagination tests (page size, page tokens) to ensure proper handling of large datasets.
Add caching header tests (ETag, Cache-Control) and cache invalidation/validation scenarios.
Add rate-limiting tests (429) and throttling behavior under load; include retry logic verification.
Add tests for 403 Forbidden scenarios and token refresh/expiry flows in authorization coverage.
If UI is involved, expand accessibility coverage beyond screen-reader compatibility to ensure full semantic accessibility in API-integrated UIs.
